âœ”ï¸ Make sure to be yourself The pressure can make you want to be, as the kids say, "extra." Instead, be yourself and trust that God will use YOU just as you are.

âœ”ï¸ Give it a run-through This is generally good advice, but I especially like to give a run-through because â€” with 5 Easter services â€” I have a shorter time limit. It helps to make sure I hit time and keeps me from practicing on the people.

âœ”ï¸ Make sense to kids and guests With more kids and guests in the service than normal, communicate in a way that will engage and make sense to them. Skip the churchy jargon. Include a funny story that would grab a 2nd-grader's attention. Make them think, "I'd like to come back."

âœ”ï¸ Emphasize the cross on Good Friday, not on Easter Too many Easter sermons sound like Good Friday sermons. Yes, the cross is glorious. But Easter is about Jesus' victory over death. Of course, they go together ("the Christ event"). But make sure Easter feels like Easter.

âœ”ï¸ Don't get too cute There's always a temptation to get overly "creative" for Easter. After all, it's a familiar story that you want to be interesting. Resist that urge â€” this thing isn't about you and your ingenuity. Preach a simple, clear gospel message.
